03:08.600 --> 03:13.360
So let's do a quick timeline of free and open source software.

03:13.360 --> 03:18.360
This is very abridged, so I'm leaving out parts for brevity so we can have a discussion

03:18.360 --> 03:20.240
and focus on other things.

03:20.240 --> 03:27.960
But in general, for this talk, I want to bisect the history of FOSS into two periods.

03:27.960 --> 03:32.880
And these dates are very generalized, but the first period I would argue is between

03:32.880 --> 03:37.040
the 70s and the early naughts.

03:37.040 --> 03:43.000
Really during the beginning of this period, computing hardware was just becoming starting

03:43.000 --> 03:44.640
to become standardized.

03:44.640 --> 03:49.000
Previously, if you bought a computing machine, it would come with the software provided by

03:49.000 --> 03:54.600
the manufacturer, and it was custom made for that model, and you couldn't easily transfer

03:54.600 --> 03:58.320
software from one model by one manufacturer into another.

03:58.320 --> 04:03.000
But soon after, hardware architectures became standardized.

04:03.000 --> 04:06.580
And so people could write software that runs on many different kinds of machines.

04:06.580 --> 04:08.120
They could share it with each other.

04:08.120 --> 04:09.640
They could trade it.

04:09.640 --> 04:14.080
And software became what's called a commodity.

04:14.080 --> 04:20.560
And so this generated all sorts of new industries that I'm sure you're all aware of within information

04:20.560 --> 04:23.080
technology and so on.

04:23.080 --> 04:28.560
And as part of this, businesses formed to develop and sell software and services around

04:28.560 --> 04:29.560
that software.

04:29.560 --> 04:35.820
And at the same time, so too did communities of practice, of production, that sort of formed

04:35.820 --> 04:42.840
the early ideas of what we imagine as open source or free software communities.

04:42.840 --> 04:50.000
And so from this situation, arose the beginnings of what I would call one of the foundational

04:50.000 --> 04:54.200
ideological pillars of free and open source software.

04:54.200 --> 05:00.320
In particular, Richard Stallman proposed these four essential rights or freedoms for users

05:00.320 --> 05:09.200
as this core ideological pillar of what free software should allow and be about.

05:09.200 --> 05:14.320
These aren't licensing terms, but rather a stance ideologically.

05:14.320 --> 05:22.880
Specifically, it's for any software user obtains, they should be able to use it for whatever

05:22.880 --> 05:24.080
purpose they want.

05:24.080 --> 05:26.360
They should be able to understand how it works.

05:26.360 --> 05:30.040
They should be able to share it onward to whoever they think might want it.

05:30.040 --> 05:35.520
And they should be able to modify it to suit their own needs and improve it potentially.

05:35.520 --> 05:41.360
And so one thing I'm really interested in considering during this period is the underlying

05:41.360 --> 05:49.420
assumptions and technological context during when these four freedoms were initially positive.

05:49.420 --> 05:54.520
At this time, most software was this very discreet thing that oftentimes came in a box

05:54.520 --> 05:57.480
or on a floppy disk or whatever.

05:57.480 --> 06:02.800
And when you ran it, it was on your own machine, it was limited in its size and complexity,

06:02.800 --> 06:09.960
it was portable and understandable largely, and it was discreet.

06:09.960 --> 06:16.860
So many businesses at the time would license their software in this way that explicitly

06:16.860 --> 06:20.240
forbade these rights.

06:20.240 --> 06:24.120
You can download my copy of Windows, but you have to pay for it and you can't modify it

06:24.120 --> 06:26.480
and you can't do whatever.

06:26.480 --> 06:30.680
And so this causes tension between these communities of developers creating free and open source

06:30.680 --> 06:35.720
software and businesses who were specifically seeking to profit off of their ability to

06:35.720 --> 06:40.160
generate revenue through these proprietary licensing strategies.

06:40.160 --> 06:45.960
You know, Bill Gates had this infamous quote where he referred to free software activists

06:45.960 --> 06:48.920
at the time as communists on a television interview.

06:48.920 --> 06:56.460
And I would argue if you talk to folks from this period, many free software organizations

06:56.460 --> 07:02.560
actually struggled with being labeled as communists or anarchists at the time.

07:02.560 --> 07:06.040
And so this was kind of almost like a meme.

07:06.040 --> 07:13.800
And just as a disclaimer here before I get sued, this poster wasn't made by Microsoft.

07:13.800 --> 07:18.200
So this poster was a meme created by someone else.

07:18.200 --> 07:23.000
So this is not representing Microsoft's views at the time or now.

07:23.000 --> 07:28.720
So Microsoft, please do not sue me for false light.

07:28.720 --> 07:34.640
So anyways, this struggle led to there being many projects and products, both open source

07:34.640 --> 07:37.240
and proprietary, right?

07:37.240 --> 07:41.200
Oftentimes, like competing products, right?

07:41.200 --> 07:45.640
And many businesses offered their own solutions that actively marketed against open source

07:45.640 --> 07:50.840
software alternatives that were trying to accomplish the same goals, fulfill the same

07:50.840 --> 07:55.680
features as their proprietary counterparts, right?

07:55.680 --> 08:00.320
And these businesses, a lot of their ideas at the time is they're relying on their greater

08:00.320 --> 08:07.280
cohesion to try to build a better product and software ecosystem when compared to their

08:07.280 --> 08:10.080
sometimes fragmented open source alternative.

08:10.080 --> 08:16.280
And this is how they seek to try to capture the market for any given use case, right?

08:16.280 --> 08:22.560
So in short, we had this situation where we see directly competing products whose common

08:22.560 --> 08:25.480
differentiator is really their licensing strategy.

08:25.480 --> 08:29.160
This is the thing that made them stand out apart from each other, right?

08:29.160 --> 08:34.960
You got Windows and Linux, you got Firefox and Internet Explorer, you got OpenGL and DirectX,

08:34.960 --> 08:35.960
right?

08:35.960 --> 08:40.640
All these were competing products to see which was better.

08:40.640 --> 08:48.160
And all these cases as a competition between which organization, the community or the firm,

08:48.160 --> 08:51.560
could build what capacities more effectively, right?

08:51.560 --> 08:57.840
And many of our debates and discussion at the time revolved around which method of production

08:57.840 --> 09:01.480
was more efficient at building these capacities.

09:01.480 --> 09:06.840
And I'm sure even if you go around today or you talk to your friends, we still hear these

09:06.840 --> 09:07.840
discussions, right?

09:07.840 --> 09:12.840
When we're talking about trying to encourage people to develop open source, it's more effective.

09:12.840 --> 09:15.400
It's just easier, we can share costs.

09:15.400 --> 09:22.280
And so during this time, licensing was this huge part, if not the most important part,

09:22.280 --> 09:26.720
of when we thought about the battle between free and open source software and proprietary

09:26.720 --> 09:27.720
software ecosystems.

09:27.720 --> 09:33.040
You know, IP rights at the time were really coming to a fore with the advent of a lot

09:33.040 --> 09:36.120
of digital intellectual property.

09:36.120 --> 09:43.320
And when considering this initial ideology focused on user autonomy, freedom, user autonomy

09:43.320 --> 09:49.960
and freedom, this idea of IP ownership in order to facilitate that through licensing

09:49.960 --> 09:56.380
was like the sort of core method that many people thought about how to achieve this sort

09:56.380 --> 10:00.920
of more ideological goal, right?

10:00.920 --> 10:07.200
So now I want to kind of jump ahead to the sort of second phase where we are today, right?

10:07.200 --> 10:12.560
So this relationship between open source and proprietary software, it didn't really stay

10:12.560 --> 10:14.400
this way, right?

10:14.400 --> 10:18.560
Now as we all know, as you come to any one of these conferences, you've probably seen

10:18.560 --> 10:21.440
this statistic already today.

10:21.440 --> 10:25.680
Free and open source software has become this foundational infrastructure upon which like

10:25.680 --> 10:29.880
pretty much all of our digital services are built, right?

10:29.880 --> 10:35.720
And before I go ahead, I just want to drop like a thank you and a note that a lot of

10:35.720 --> 10:41.320
the graphs I'm going to be showing in the next couple of slides come from this amazing

10:41.320 --> 10:46.120
2021 report written by the Digital Commons Policy Council.

10:46.120 --> 10:50.480
So I got a link to that policy council in the slides, which you can download off of

10:50.480 --> 10:51.720
the FOSDEM website.

10:51.720 --> 10:56.120
I encourage you to check it out, but they did a lot of really great work for getting

10:56.120 --> 11:01.000
the data and the empirical sort of findings here.

11:01.000 --> 11:05.840
So anyways, you know, today we see some of the biggest antagonists towards free and open

11:05.840 --> 11:10.840
source software actually directing the most significant amounts of their workforce towards

11:10.840 --> 11:15.240
its support and budget, especially when compared to other firms, right?

11:15.240 --> 11:19.040
Microsoft was like the big bad in open source, right?

11:19.040 --> 11:23.360
And now they're actually one of the largest contributors of it, right?

11:23.360 --> 11:26.800
They're very much bought into open source software production.

11:26.800 --> 11:32.720
You know, not only have major firms changed their tune in relationship to each other,

11:32.720 --> 11:37.320
but now when we look at open source communities in the largest projects and most important

11:37.320 --> 11:42.880
projects on the internet, employees of these firms now generally outnumber independent

11:42.880 --> 11:43.880
contributors.

11:43.880 --> 11:48.800
And, you know, I'm careful to use the term independent here rather than volunteer because

11:48.800 --> 11:54.480
independent contributors are oftentimes contributing in the context of like an organization or

11:54.480 --> 12:01.240
institution, but it's not really one that is focused specifically on maximizing profit

12:01.240 --> 12:02.600
for themselves.

12:02.600 --> 12:07.640
So these types of contributors, I would argue, face like very different incentives in terms

12:07.640 --> 12:10.720
of like what they're trying to build and for what purpose.

12:10.720 --> 12:19.240
Furthermore, you know, as time has gone on, the ratio of firm employees to the independent

12:19.240 --> 12:23.040
contributor has increased steadily, right?

12:23.040 --> 12:29.800
So year over year in most or in pretty much all major projects, the amount of firm employees

12:29.800 --> 12:33.880
when compared to non-firm employees has increased, right?

12:33.880 --> 12:40.200
So this is not just like a finding, but it's a year over year trend that's increasing steadily.

12:40.200 --> 12:47.320
So I would argue one thing to note in this case then is that we can sort of find that

12:47.320 --> 12:52.680
independent contributors oftentimes have less power in these communities simply because

12:52.680 --> 12:59.360
they're being outnumbered by a much more cohesive group of other contributors and they just

12:59.360 --> 13:04.360
have less power to develop, right?

13:04.360 --> 13:10.160
And so while these projects are majorly developed at the explicit discretion of firms, right?

13:10.160 --> 13:15.960
What I think is most important is actually the shift between these two periods is actually

13:15.960 --> 13:22.660
how the form of software itself has shifted when thinking about open source software.

13:22.660 --> 13:27.840
So if you look at this list of projects, so this was I think the top 20 or 25 projects

13:27.840 --> 13:33.720
that the, in terms of like contributors and activity founded by the Digital Commons Policy

13:33.720 --> 13:35.240
Council.

13:35.240 --> 13:40.520
And if you look at this list, nearly all of these projects, they aren't really end user

13:40.520 --> 13:44.240
software anymore, even of the technical sort, right?

13:44.240 --> 13:49.880
Many are for use solely in the development of these sort of large scale products and

13:49.880 --> 13:57.160
platforms that can really only be applicable to users who have significant resources to

13:57.160 --> 13:58.720
run them, right?

13:58.720 --> 14:02.880
So like let's have a look, right?

14:02.880 --> 14:10.200
We got a number of server orchestration software such as like Kubernetes, Moby or Ansible.

14:10.200 --> 14:15.200
We also have machine learning and distributed systems projects such as like Spark, PyTorch

14:15.200 --> 14:16.200
and TensorFlow.

14:16.200 --> 14:22.200
And I'm sure as you attend talks today, even at Fostom, a conference that's quite community

14:22.200 --> 14:26.680
focused, you'll likely find the majority of software programs being discussed are of this

14:26.680 --> 14:27.840
type.

14:27.840 --> 14:34.040
So why has the production of free and open source software shifted so incredibly to this

14:34.040 --> 14:41.340
one very kind of specific niche within software applications?

14:41.340 --> 14:48.040
So I'd like to argue that most of the software we interact with on a day to day basis, and

14:48.040 --> 14:54.320
you know maybe I'm leaning out of the free software developer archetype here when I'm

14:54.320 --> 14:59.400
saying this, but most of the software we interact with aren't really discrete applications

14:59.400 --> 15:03.600
anymore but rather what I would call platforms, right?

15:03.600 --> 15:09.360
And because of this, the relationship of much of our open source software and our proprietary

15:09.360 --> 15:13.120
software has like fundamentally changed, right?

15:13.120 --> 15:18.080
So why are these projects that are, you know, important now so different than the projects

15:18.080 --> 15:19.480
that were important before?

15:19.480 --> 15:24.920
Now I'd like to argue that many of the most powerful technology firms have largely pivoted

15:24.920 --> 15:30.960
away from licensing discrete software products as their core sort of revenue model to the

15:30.960 --> 15:38.280
development and, you know, managing of platforms to generate revenue for them.

15:38.280 --> 15:43.120
So you know, before we go forward, I'm sure you've all heard the term platform before,

15:43.120 --> 15:47.640
but I'd like to try to formally define it in economic terms, right?

15:47.640 --> 15:53.880
And so this sort of, I'm paraphrasing here, but this definition was first posited by

15:53.880 --> 15:59.200
a Nobel Prize winning economist, learner and to roll.

15:59.200 --> 16:03.600
So platforms, when we think about a platform, you oftentimes think about it like a software

16:03.600 --> 16:05.920
system or something like that, right?

16:05.920 --> 16:11.640
But these software systems aren't really commodities in themselves, but rather they're made as

16:11.640 --> 16:18.000
a system to manage access between like networks on two sides of a wall or like commodities

16:18.000 --> 16:19.840
on two sides of a wall.

16:19.840 --> 16:26.720
So to give an example of this, you know, Facebook is a platform which manages access to communities

16:26.720 --> 16:32.720
in media for end users on one side and then, you know, willing eyes, data and ad positioning

16:32.720 --> 16:34.960
for advertisers on the other side.

16:34.960 --> 16:39.440
And Facebook has kind of this monopolized access to both of these networks, right?

16:39.440 --> 16:42.640
Or at least like a very preferential access to both.

16:42.640 --> 16:49.680
You know, Amazon is a platform which facilitates access to distribution networks in a global

16:49.680 --> 16:55.040
marketplace for producers on one side and then a network of goods and services for consumers

16:55.040 --> 16:56.960
on the other side.

16:56.960 --> 17:01.040
Google is a platform which facilitates information and digital services for end users on one

17:01.040 --> 17:06.140
side and again, you know, willing eyes and user networks for those digital service providers

17:06.140 --> 17:08.240
and advertisers on the other.

17:08.240 --> 17:13.280
So the nature of the platform has positioned their creators to exploit what are called

17:13.280 --> 17:20.280
these multi-sided markets with these sort of two networks by acting as a mediator and

17:20.280 --> 17:27.760
a gatekeeper between access across this sort of divide.

17:27.760 --> 17:34.320
So you know, I'd like to posit this question to everyone that we always hear all the time.

17:34.320 --> 17:36.800
It's honestly probably getting a little old in the tooth.

17:36.800 --> 17:39.040
But you know, has open source won?

17:39.040 --> 17:40.680
Like you know, have we done it?

17:40.680 --> 17:44.880
We are foundational to the operation of like the entire world.

17:44.880 --> 17:47.440
You know, open source is really important.

17:47.440 --> 17:50.360
More people than ever are creating it, right?

17:50.360 --> 17:53.840
And so, you know, no, I don't think so.

17:53.840 --> 17:56.720
I mean, there's clearly more open source, right?

17:56.720 --> 18:01.600
There's probably a similar or larger proportion of open source software to proprietary software

18:01.600 --> 18:05.280
that we use on a daily basis, at least within the dependency chain.

18:05.280 --> 18:12.160
However, we still have little to no control over the vast majority of services that impact

18:12.160 --> 18:16.000
most people's lives, particularly digital services, right?

18:16.000 --> 18:22.200
From e-commerce to social media to healthcare provision, all of these, you know, might heavily

18:22.200 --> 18:26.280
rely on free and open source infrastructure to function.

18:26.280 --> 18:29.840
But we still have no actual control.

18:29.840 --> 18:35.120
So when we think about the ideological pillars of our movement in the first place, I don't

18:35.120 --> 18:39.000
see any significant gains in this area.

18:39.000 --> 18:45.280
So you know, to me, when looking at this history, it really seemed that many free and open source

18:45.280 --> 18:53.160
advocacy programs have been out-maneuvered in this way due to the shape of our software

18:53.160 --> 18:54.160
changing.

18:54.160 --> 19:00.160
So, you know, I know that's like a little depressing and everything.

19:00.160 --> 19:05.760
And I'm sure many people have a lot of opinions about maybe the validity of that.

19:05.760 --> 19:12.040
But I kind of want to talk about, well, if this is the case, right, and if this is a

19:12.040 --> 19:18.080
problem that we as a community are facing, then what do we do about it, right?

19:18.080 --> 19:24.400
So first I want to kind of review a couple of key points that I wanted to make.

19:24.400 --> 19:30.240
And then I want to, I know this is like a stage talk, but I want to have a lot of Q&A

19:30.240 --> 19:35.400
afterwards to have a discussion with the audience.

19:35.400 --> 19:40.320
So first and foremost, you know, I want to claim, you know, free and open source software

19:40.320 --> 19:45.080
isn't competing with proprietary software anymore in any significant way.

19:45.080 --> 19:52.640
I know there's, you know, probably examples, but when we look at the largest, most active,

19:52.640 --> 19:58.360
most important free and open source software projects, they are not competing with proprietary

19:58.360 --> 19:59.360
alternatives.

19:59.360 --> 20:01.480
They're helping host them, right?

20:01.480 --> 20:07.120
The second is our labor as free and open source software contributors in general is being

20:07.120 --> 20:09.720
increasingly dictated by firms.

20:09.720 --> 20:15.480
We see this year on year because we're being continually outnumbered by firm contributors.

20:15.480 --> 20:19.080
And we're having less of a say in the communities that we act in.

20:19.080 --> 20:24.960
You know, furthermore, more of us are working directly for firms when contributing and are

20:24.960 --> 20:28.040
therefore, you know, required to represent their interests.

20:28.040 --> 20:32.720
And even when we aren't, certainly the most important projects, our ability to dictate

20:32.720 --> 20:35.760
the direction of these is, you know, we're outnumbered.

20:35.760 --> 20:41.280
On the flip side, we are finding when these firms suffer any loss in their rate of profit,

20:41.280 --> 20:45.580
usually it is us who are among the first to be cut, right?

20:45.580 --> 20:50.920
This precarity and increasing control that firms have over our collective labor powers

20:50.920 --> 20:58.760
means that oftentimes we're losing autonomy as creators over our own labor.

20:58.760 --> 21:03.920
You know, so this original framing of user control over, you know, our software that

21:03.920 --> 21:09.480
we download and run on our machines, you know, I would argue is no longer relevant because

21:09.480 --> 21:16.120
we live in a time where, you know, we majority interact with these really complex, massive

21:16.120 --> 21:17.120
platforms.

21:17.120 --> 21:20.960
Most critical software we interact with is no longer these discrete packages offering

21:20.960 --> 21:26.140
specific functionality to users, but rather, you know, these platforms are gating and mediating

21:26.140 --> 21:30.880
access between markets, commodities, and other networks, right?

21:30.880 --> 21:36.200
Therefore, our original conception of simply increasing the amount of openly licensed software

21:36.200 --> 21:41.520
products is no longer as relevant as the projects we're building are largely infrastructure

21:41.520 --> 21:45.400
to maintain these platforms, right?

21:45.400 --> 21:51.400
So we can no longer avoid this very political question about how we attempt to reorganize

21:51.400 --> 21:58.000
free and open source software labor on behalf of these original ideals of, you know, user

21:58.000 --> 21:59.000
rights.

21:59.000 --> 22:03.680
You know, labor organization has frequently been a topic avoided previously in free and

22:03.680 --> 22:09.440
open source software, and I would argue it was due to this major focus on licensing instead.

22:09.440 --> 22:14.000
You know, we didn't talk about, like, who we're working for or how we're organizing

22:14.000 --> 22:18.840
our work because we wanted to focus on where the ownership was, and if we can create more,

22:18.840 --> 22:25.200
you know, open licensed things, then the ownership goes to everyone, and then the power is distributed,

22:25.200 --> 22:29.340
and I would argue we've seen that we've been kind of outmaneuvered in that sense because

22:29.340 --> 22:35.160
our interaction with owned software has largely changed.

22:35.160 --> 22:39.880
So you know, this all sounds not great, but if this is the case, then how can we adopt

22:39.880 --> 22:45.080
a more sort of labor-oriented approach to the topic of free and open source values and

22:45.080 --> 22:46.360
ideals, right?

22:46.360 --> 22:54.400
How can you as a foster or me, you know, I'm not off the hook here, help bring about this

22:54.400 --> 22:55.400
change?

22:55.400 --> 22:59.720
So, you know, I can't claim to have all the answers here.

22:59.720 --> 23:05.280
You know, I'm just a guy interested in this topic studying this stuff.

23:05.280 --> 23:09.120
Especially now, you know, I understand the topic of political change is a very touchy

23:09.120 --> 23:10.120
one.

23:10.120 --> 23:13.800
However, there are some ideas I've researched that I think would be, you know, at least

23:13.800 --> 23:18.360
worthwhile for us as a community to investigate further.

23:18.360 --> 23:23.760
The first is the idea of understanding that not all free and open source software contributions

23:23.760 --> 23:25.080
are equal.

23:25.080 --> 23:31.080
So when considering the value of free and open source software contributions, you know,

23:31.080 --> 23:35.960
maybe we should prioritize developing alternatives to existing platforms that are controlled

23:35.960 --> 23:37.660
by firms, right?

23:37.660 --> 23:41.960
And so when I say alternative here, I don't just mean an openly licensed clone, but rather

23:41.960 --> 23:48.520
a solution designed specifically with these ideals of user autonomy in mind, right?

23:48.520 --> 23:54.680
It may take an entirely different form to create something that would be comparable.

23:54.680 --> 23:58.680
The second I want to talk about that I think is very important is organizing within the

23:58.680 --> 23:59.680
workplace.

23:59.680 --> 24:04.640
You know, I've met many, many, many burnt out free and open source software maintainers

24:04.640 --> 24:08.040
in my life, and I understand the pain there.

24:08.040 --> 24:12.480
And so, you know, our ability to produce what we want requires that we have greater control

24:12.480 --> 24:14.440
over our own labor.

24:14.440 --> 24:21.880
So while technology roles are oftentimes compensated well, at least within certain geographic

24:21.880 --> 24:28.280
areas, it doesn't eliminate our precarity as workers, right?

24:28.280 --> 24:32.920
And I think in particular, many of us are finding that out now.

24:32.920 --> 24:35.640
So in this case, what do we do about it?

24:35.640 --> 24:40.000
Well, historically, the formulation of labor unions have allowed us as workers to better

24:40.000 --> 24:44.480
bargain with our employees and regain control over our labor power.

24:44.480 --> 24:51.040
And I think when thinking about how we can manage to have the time and capacity to be

24:51.040 --> 24:55.800
able to build what we want, thinking about regaining that control within your own workplace,

24:55.800 --> 25:01.040
particularly through labor unions, is a great first step.

25:01.040 --> 25:05.360
The third thing I want to talk about, which is a little touchy, is explicit political

25:05.360 --> 25:09.920
organizing within the context of our free and open source software community.

25:09.920 --> 25:13.880
I don't think we can just build and license the solutions that we want, but rather we

25:13.880 --> 25:19.600
need to organize ourselves along explicit political lines that go beyond that of licensing.

25:19.600 --> 25:23.800
When you think about free and open source software, I was in Bradley Kuhn's talk today

25:23.800 --> 25:27.800
in the legal dev room where he was kind of talking about his personal history in this

25:27.800 --> 25:33.720
case and he talked about how there were a lot of, I forget the word he used, but like

25:33.720 --> 25:38.240
collaborations between groups that had different interests, right?

25:38.240 --> 25:40.560
And he was questioning, he was like, you know, I don't know if we should have worked with

25:40.560 --> 25:42.600
them or worked with someone else.

25:42.600 --> 25:48.160
And I think it's very hard to determine these sort of partnerships that you enter unless

25:48.160 --> 25:54.040
you have a very clear political line that you as a community are agreeing to work together

25:54.040 --> 25:55.040
on.

25:55.040 --> 25:59.240
And I think defining this is really important, probably just as important as something like

25:59.240 --> 26:01.440
the open source definition.

26:01.440 --> 26:08.280
Lastly, you know, I think finding and developing new workplaces is going to be a really important

26:08.280 --> 26:13.560
fact when thinking about, you know, kind of figuring out how we can organize ourselves

26:13.560 --> 26:16.320
to develop the software that we want, right?

26:16.320 --> 26:21.280
I get that this isn't an option for everyone immediately, but, you know, the role of institutions

26:21.280 --> 26:27.280
such as, you know, NGOs, nonprofits and universities have historically been, you know, key creators

26:27.280 --> 26:31.400
of foundational free and open source software infrastructures.

26:31.400 --> 26:36.040
And furthermore, I think we as a community see our ability to represent ourselves lessening

26:36.040 --> 26:37.600
in general, right?

26:37.600 --> 26:42.840
You look at organizations like the Linux Foundation and they pretty much exclusively represent

26:42.840 --> 26:47.000
the interests of their corporate members, that is literally how they're incorporated,

26:47.000 --> 26:48.000
right?

26:48.000 --> 26:51.280
And they have no public good mandate.

26:51.280 --> 26:55.920
So I would argue that we should organize, agitate and push for these institutions and

26:55.920 --> 27:02.800
our society to support this production to draw power away from firms.

27:02.800 --> 27:09.120
So now this is a bit tongue in cheek, you know, I'm not claiming you should all be communists,

27:09.120 --> 27:15.320
but this is my poorly made rendition of the earlier poster.

27:15.320 --> 27:20.440
I want to wrap up with, you know, free and open source software, you know, I would argue

27:20.440 --> 27:26.820
was largely outmaneuvered due to this lack of cohesion and organization within a specified

27:26.820 --> 27:28.560
political framework.

27:28.560 --> 27:34.160
And so if we do, you know, seek to reorganize ourselves for a new era in free and open source

27:34.160 --> 27:39.920
software, then we should consider how we got here and, you know, see if we can correct

27:39.920 --> 27:42.880
some of those mistakes.

