32:51.840 --> 33:00.720
So I would argue that for sure as technologists we face unique labor pressures.

33:00.720 --> 33:08.280
In particular, I was at the EU policy forum thing yesterday and there are a lot of policy

33:08.280 --> 33:14.960
people that go up and they're like, technology, the coders are going to save the planet because

33:14.960 --> 33:21.880
they're genius and they kind of, we get a lot of lip service towards our technical ability.

33:21.880 --> 33:28.480
But on the flip side I would argue that we still face many of the same precarities that

33:28.480 --> 33:32.760
people have, that we've seen workers have throughout history.

33:32.760 --> 33:39.080
And for sure it's a struggle and it's a discussion we need to have as we're organizing ourselves.

33:39.080 --> 33:46.680
But I think first and foremost, if we want to have better free and open source software,

33:46.680 --> 33:51.000
we got to have more control over our own labor power to create it.

33:51.000 --> 33:55.640
We've done a lot of really cool stuff just like as hobbyists and things like that.

33:55.640 --> 34:01.800
Imagine if there was an army of us all working together and dictating like, oh, this is what

34:01.800 --> 34:02.800
we want.

34:02.800 --> 34:03.800
I don't want Facebook.

34:03.800 --> 34:06.080
Who likes Facebook anyways?

34:06.080 --> 34:10.200
I want to build the thing that's actually allowing me to connect with people and the

34:10.200 --> 34:13.200
ways that I dictate is best for me.

34:13.200 --> 34:16.520
It takes a lot of organization and agitation to get there.

34:16.520 --> 34:24.760
And I think even as intellectuals or a person in the professional managerial class, we still

34:24.760 --> 34:27.920
have a lot of incentive to work at that.

34:27.920 --> 34:29.000
