34:31.520 --> 34:41.200
Yeah, so when open source was being developed in discrete ways for discrete products, there

34:41.200 --> 34:48.320
was no cost to the developers of the software when someone used that software in whatever

34:48.320 --> 34:49.320
setting.

34:49.320 --> 34:53.440
So you could produce a thousand or a million and the open source project almost didn't

34:53.440 --> 34:57.600
know who was there and who was using it.

34:57.600 --> 35:04.000
And I understand your concept that there's more of a consumption at the platform level

35:04.000 --> 35:07.600
now than discrete software.

35:07.600 --> 35:17.320
But the question is, how do projects evolve in an environment where you have to provide

35:17.320 --> 35:20.800
now there is now a cost to that platform?

35:20.800 --> 35:25.080
So you've got to have infrastructure, you've got to have networking, you've got to have

35:25.080 --> 35:27.240
admins and so forth.

35:27.240 --> 35:35.480
And there's now a per user cost in a lot of ways to how your software is consumed in a

35:35.480 --> 35:37.560
way that before it was zero cost.

35:37.560 --> 35:43.520
And it feels like that change is pretty significant and does almost open the door or close the

35:43.520 --> 35:51.000
door frankly for pure open source projects to almost operate at scale in that environment.

35:51.000 --> 35:54.280
Yeah, great question.

35:54.280 --> 35:59.920
And very, very relevant and not one I think I have the answer to.

35:59.920 --> 36:08.520
But I want to maybe propose a couple of potential answers that I think I can't choose.

36:08.520 --> 36:10.240
We have to choose.

36:10.240 --> 36:15.320
And so when thinking about platforms, there's a lot of different ways.

36:15.320 --> 36:17.840
Currently many platforms are kind of exploitative.

36:17.840 --> 36:21.600
We don't really have a choice in terms of whether or not we use them if we want to have

36:21.600 --> 36:26.560
access to a certain thing like social networks or whatever.

36:26.560 --> 36:30.720
So part of it's like, oh, maybe we just need to collectively own it.

36:30.720 --> 36:32.800
Maybe just nationalize it.

36:32.800 --> 36:39.000
It's one very political way of thinking about solving this problem.

36:39.000 --> 36:43.120
If we nationalize it, then it's democratically controlled theoretically.

36:43.120 --> 36:47.560
This is one way of approaching this problem of user autonomy.

36:47.560 --> 36:53.800
Then if someone wants to change it, then we have democracy to help facilitate that somehow.

36:53.800 --> 36:59.080
Another way of approaching the problem though is do we need platforms at all?

36:59.080 --> 37:06.680
Is this approach of one specific technological solution to solving one specific need within

37:06.680 --> 37:08.080
our society?

37:08.080 --> 37:11.640
Is this the right way of going about it, or was this just the most effective way of running

37:11.640 --> 37:12.840
it?

37:12.840 --> 37:19.040
Can we imagine futures of which our technology is progressing, but it's still discrete enough

37:19.040 --> 37:21.160
that we can maintain control over it?

37:21.160 --> 37:24.040
And then what does that look like, and how do we get there?

37:24.040 --> 37:32.960
I think these are the different arguments and maybe factions that might arise within

37:32.960 --> 37:34.280
the open source community.

37:34.280 --> 37:40.960
I think if we start begin really rethinking what we're doing on a more fundamental level.

37:40.960 --> 37:43.520
Does that sort of?

