38:44.000 --> 38:50.440
I have a lot of friends, and as part of my research, I do lots of research with how unions

38:50.440 --> 38:55.080
currently organize and how they use technology.

38:55.080 --> 39:02.720
So there's not one... Everyone I talk to, whenever I ask them this question, they're

39:02.720 --> 39:06.640
like, well, I can't give you a blueprint, but I can tell you some things that work for

39:06.640 --> 39:10.640
us.

39:10.640 --> 39:17.320
I work with a couple union organizers at Amazon, and they have huge turnover.

39:17.320 --> 39:23.920
So focusing on new employees as a point of organizing and getting people and educating

39:23.920 --> 39:26.200
them is very important for them.

39:26.200 --> 39:31.880
I have another friend that works as a technician in a hospital who has a very small department.

39:31.880 --> 39:37.120
And when they started focusing on unionizing, or at least collectively bargaining amongst

39:37.120 --> 39:43.520
themselves, they started in a very small but critical part of their organization, saying,

39:43.520 --> 39:45.680
we can't do the whole hospital at once.

39:45.680 --> 39:48.440
We'll just get fired, right?

39:48.440 --> 39:51.680
We'll have a bad time, and it'll be very hard, and we don't have the capacity.

39:51.680 --> 39:57.600
But maybe within our department, if we begin forming certain lines about what we want and

39:57.600 --> 40:02.660
what we care about, we can begin starting our organization from there and then moving

40:02.660 --> 40:05.280
outward if we gain momentum.

40:05.280 --> 40:13.360
I think particularly within the technological context and people within tech companies,

40:13.360 --> 40:17.000
this might be an interesting thing to try out.

40:17.000 --> 40:23.040
But that said, we haven't seen, we don't have a lot to learn from in this sense, right?

40:23.040 --> 40:29.600
