41:11.920 --> 41:20.800
And certainly, when I hear a lot of folks talking about, I think it's, I would argue,

41:20.800 --> 41:24.920
and I know I called out many companies here, but I would argue the Linux Foundation is

41:24.920 --> 41:29.680
quite different from most open source software foundations.

41:29.680 --> 41:35.520
Linux Foundation is a membership organization that is formed specifically to represent its

41:35.520 --> 41:36.520
corporate members.

41:36.520 --> 41:39.080
They're looking for a membership to get into the Linux Foundation.

41:39.080 --> 41:42.080
They have a summit and stuff like that.

41:42.080 --> 41:47.320
And they're supposed to advocate on your right, on behalf of your interests, as a tech company

41:47.320 --> 41:49.400
that utilizes open source.

41:49.400 --> 41:53.280
They've grown quite a lot due to their funding.

41:53.280 --> 41:57.960
I would argue that's very different from something like the Python Software Foundation or the

41:57.960 --> 42:03.360
Rust Foundation or even Apache or something like that.

42:03.360 --> 42:08.400
I would argue, I would like to see more collaboration.

42:08.400 --> 42:13.280
I don't think software foundations for every project that exist in their own little ecosystem.

42:13.280 --> 42:17.400
I think that's good, so you can receive funding and stuff like that.

42:17.400 --> 42:22.800
But we should start figuring out ways that, what if there was a Linux Foundation that

42:22.800 --> 42:29.560
wasn't driven principally by members who paid for ownership?

42:29.560 --> 42:33.440
Maybe we could think about things like, oh, I know the top contributors might get membership

42:33.440 --> 42:40.080
if you contribute a certain amount or some other form.

42:40.080 --> 42:42.840
There's a lot of different ways that you could go about it.

42:42.840 --> 42:48.280
But I think figuring out how to bring communities together with similar interests, even if they

42:48.280 --> 42:54.480
aren't the same project or in the same tech stack, is important because then you can begin

42:54.480 --> 43:00.440
organizing along ideological lines rather than just like, how do we make Wayland work

43:00.440 --> 43:06.800
better in Nome or something?

43:06.800 --> 43:16.320
I feel like there are a lot of pieces to dismantling these platforms.

43:16.320 --> 43:21.780
I feel like a few of them are being discussed around here, like the cooperative company

43:21.780 --> 43:29.000
structures and building new open platforms.

43:29.000 --> 43:35.960
But when it comes to unionizing, because there aren't really many tech unions, I've been

43:35.960 --> 43:39.160
thinking a lot about how these would work.

43:39.160 --> 43:48.200
And I wondered what your thoughts were on the idea of using tech unions to try and dismantle

43:48.200 --> 43:54.280
some of the existing platforms, like say, we're not going to work on AWS because we

43:54.280 --> 43:57.600
don't agree with Amazon and what it's doing with its other employees, for example.

43:57.600 --> 44:02.840
What are your thoughts on that way of approaching this kind of thing?

44:02.840 --> 44:03.840
Yeah.

44:03.840 --> 44:12.000
I would say one step at a time.

44:12.000 --> 44:16.280
Before giving the talk, obviously I talked about this subject to a lot of people.

44:16.280 --> 44:19.200
And there's a sense of, like, things are pretty bad now.

44:19.200 --> 44:21.160
How are we supposed to deal with all this stuff?

44:21.160 --> 44:22.560
It feels like everything's collapsing.

44:22.560 --> 44:25.600
We're kind of in survival mode.

44:25.600 --> 44:33.480
I would argue, at least right now, at this moment, the real benefit of unionizing within

44:33.480 --> 44:40.600
technology workplaces is it gives a little bit more time and autonomy and stability back

44:40.600 --> 44:43.200
to technology workers.

44:43.200 --> 44:49.800
And so when I think about the crisis and open source around volunteers who are just overburdened

44:49.800 --> 44:54.400
and stuff, and I think about everyone I know that works in tech that's on call all the

44:54.400 --> 45:00.040
time and software services are crashing and now their coworkers are being laid off or

45:00.040 --> 45:08.160
maybe they are, this is the problem that I think if we can claw back some of our own

45:08.160 --> 45:13.920
time, if we can get a little more autonomy on our own, a little more reasonable working

45:13.920 --> 45:20.040
conditions, like even I get that the pay is good in some conditions, then we can begin

45:20.040 --> 45:25.720
just having the head space to think about these new solutions and have the time to organize

45:25.720 --> 45:29.680
with each other where our boss isn't watching us either.

45:29.680 --> 45:31.080
Right?

45:31.080 --> 45:42.440
Thanks for your talk.

45:42.440 --> 45:47.640
You talked about software, but do you think we can observe the same shift from individual

45:47.640 --> 45:56.720
and independent contributors to software companies and big firms paid contributors in the international

45:56.720 --> 46:03.920
standardization organization like IETF, for example, I think about how the first version

46:03.920 --> 46:12.560
of HTTP protocol was defined and the third version which was mostly the result of a bargain

46:12.560 --> 46:15.760
between Google, Facebook and Microsoft.

46:15.760 --> 46:21.680
Is there any data or work on it?

46:21.680 --> 46:22.680
I'm sure there is.

46:22.680 --> 46:24.280
I don't have any.

46:24.280 --> 46:26.560
I have anecdotal data.

46:26.560 --> 46:34.440
I served on a couple IEEE standards committees and noticed this sort of major differentiating

46:34.440 --> 46:39.600
where you get people who are there on developing a standard specifically for the interest of

46:39.600 --> 46:40.600
their company.

46:40.600 --> 46:41.600
Right?

46:41.600 --> 46:48.520
They are like, my boss is paying me and I'm supposed to help manage this and make it so

46:48.520 --> 46:52.280
our organization can accomplish the goals that we want to do.

46:52.280 --> 46:56.320
I'm not saying it's evil to want to do that or anything like that.

46:56.320 --> 47:00.800
I see a lot of that and I don't see a lot of people who are like, I think the standard

47:00.800 --> 47:01.800
is pretty cool.

47:01.800 --> 47:06.480
I did a thing with something related one time and I want to, it's like showing up at your

47:06.480 --> 47:07.480
town hall meeting.

47:07.480 --> 47:12.680
Who has time for that anymore?

47:12.680 --> 47:17.000
I would argue the same principles are at play here.

47:17.000 --> 47:21.320
More and more organizations are interested in forming standards with each other because

47:21.320 --> 47:26.320
it helps share the cost of development of a lot of their infrastructures.

47:26.320 --> 47:30.920
No one wants to reinvent the entire stack for whatever thing they are building.

47:30.920 --> 47:36.160
By utilizing standards, you can more effectively do that the same way that you could by utilizing

47:36.160 --> 47:39.680
open source software to do that.

47:39.680 --> 47:46.280
I would say principally there are a lot of similarities but I don't have like a, I certainly,

47:46.280 --> 47:49.360
at least at this time, I couldn't empirically prove it.

47:49.360 --> 47:55.360
But a great point for further research on the road here.

47:55.360 --> 48:02.360
Right, is that better?

48:02.360 --> 48:03.360
Fascinating talk.

48:03.360 --> 48:09.840
I just wonder whether we've made life easy for the big corporations.

48:09.840 --> 48:11.560
I think we all enjoy writing software.

48:11.560 --> 48:13.560
We enjoy solving a problem.

48:13.560 --> 48:19.040
It's a bit like an academic, researching something and then you get an entrepreneur

48:19.040 --> 48:21.840
making his fortune.

48:21.840 --> 48:25.520
How can we fight back as developers?

48:25.520 --> 48:26.920
Yeah.

48:26.920 --> 48:32.640
So I guess your question is, if I understand correctly, you're kind of like, we kind of

48:32.640 --> 48:35.640
made it easy for us to get into the situation that we are in now.

48:35.640 --> 48:37.320
Like how do we fight back?

48:37.320 --> 48:38.320
Is that it?

48:38.320 --> 48:39.320
Yeah.

48:39.320 --> 48:47.760
Well, you know, I think, I'm not a huge fan of like kind of the self-flagellation where

48:47.760 --> 48:51.960
it's like, you know, we got corrupted or whatever.

48:51.960 --> 48:57.960
You know, as the last 50 years of history around, you know, the development of digital

48:57.960 --> 49:01.760
technology has a lot of very major incentives.

49:01.760 --> 49:02.760
It was very complex.

49:02.760 --> 49:08.520
It was not necessarily super obvious that we would be where we are today.

49:08.520 --> 49:13.080
You know, I think the most important thing is like, you know, the future is yours if

49:13.080 --> 49:14.920
you fight for it.

49:14.920 --> 49:16.040
Right?

49:16.040 --> 49:20.320
It's not like an easy, you know, the things I suggested, if you want to try to unionize

49:20.320 --> 49:22.520
your workplace, it's not an easy thing to do.

49:22.520 --> 49:25.880
You know, I have many people that have like tried and failed.

49:25.880 --> 49:28.760
I know many people that have succeeded as well.

49:28.760 --> 49:35.040
But, you know, I think like if this is something you want, right, if you think about like the

49:35.040 --> 49:39.840
four freedoms or these ideals of open source as like user autonomy, you're like, you know,

49:39.840 --> 49:41.080
this is the world I want to live in.

49:41.080 --> 49:46.440
And as a technologist, I can create this stuff, then, you know, like anything, it'll take

49:46.440 --> 49:47.960
work to try to do that.

49:47.960 --> 49:53.960
And it's more about recognizing that and then figuring out what to do next.

49:53.960 --> 49:58.080
I think we're at time to one more question.

49:58.080 --> 49:59.080
Thanks for this.

49:59.080 --> 50:00.840
It's really kind of a great thing.

50:00.840 --> 50:06.800
I want to ask not only you, but everyone else here, you know, do you think that we as humans

50:06.800 --> 50:13.000
can step away from that kind of that you always need to have someone like in charge?

50:13.000 --> 50:19.920
So we have that, you know, pyramidal kind of thing and that to like to go more, you

50:19.920 --> 50:20.920
know, a flat.

50:20.920 --> 50:22.560
So that's what I'm saying.

50:22.560 --> 50:29.360
So we are so used to have someone in charge and to someone, as you said, word that I don't

50:29.360 --> 50:35.800
like a lot, I can dictate to someone and dictate what you should do and actually team up.

50:35.800 --> 50:40.320
I'm not sure that we as humans really can do that on some bigger scale.

50:40.320 --> 50:41.320
It's a left.

50:41.320 --> 50:44.560
I'm very left, but I don't go far left.

50:44.560 --> 50:46.800
So I am really left side.

50:46.800 --> 50:52.040
So I'm saying that it's kind of feels like if you play in a small band and you make a

50:52.040 --> 50:54.400
nice songs and, you know, with music.

50:54.400 --> 51:00.000
And as soon as you get my mind there, you sell your soul and you're gone.

51:00.000 --> 51:06.160
So how we can go more flat without losing our soul.

51:06.160 --> 51:12.960
Yeah, I mean, it's tricky, you know, the human nature and eating someone in charge.

51:12.960 --> 51:17.200
This is a little bit of a joke here, but like, you know, I would love to introduce you to

51:17.200 --> 51:18.840
my four year old nephew.

51:18.840 --> 51:24.800
He would he might have you changing your thoughts on that very quickly with respecting authority

51:24.800 --> 51:27.840
and wanting that.

51:27.840 --> 51:33.440
I think there's no easy question about like, but you have to think about our organization

51:33.440 --> 51:35.480
scientifically, right?

51:35.480 --> 51:40.400
I don't think it's like a matter of preference, but we have to think about our relationships

51:40.400 --> 51:41.400
to each other.

51:41.400 --> 51:47.080
We have to test and evaluate various modes of organization and we have to approach it

51:47.080 --> 51:50.040
like any other difficult scientific problem in our lifetime.

51:50.040 --> 51:53.760
And, you know, through that, hopefully we can find a better solution if not the right

51:53.760 --> 51:54.760
one.

51:54.760 --> 51:55.760
Thank you.

51:55.760 --> 51:58.040
My many thanks for the amazing talk.
